<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ssl-tls-management">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>server-craft</domain>
    <summary>Configure HTTPS on a Linux VPS: Let's Encrypt (90-day auto-renew), Cloudflare origin cert (15-year, no renewal), or hybrid. Always use Cloudflare Full(Strict). nginx TLS 1.2/1.3, OCSP stapling, HSTS.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>ssl</tag>
      <tag>tls</tag>
      <tag>nginx</tag>
      <tag>cloudflare</tag>
      <tag>letsencrypt</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>SSL/TLS Management</title>
    <summary>Configure HTTPS on a Linux VPS with one of three certificate strategies: Let's Encrypt (direct exposure, 90-day auto-renew via certbot), Cloudflare origin cert (15-year cert behind Cloudflare proxy, no renewal), or hybrid. Always use Cloudflare Full(Strict) mode — never Flexible. nginx SSL hardening: TLS 1.2/1.3 only, strong ciphers, OCSP stapling (Let's Encrypt only), HSTS.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Flexible mode sends traffic from Cloudflare to the origin over plain HTTP, creating a false sense of security and causing redirect loops when nginx also forces HTTPS. A 15-year Cloudflare origin cert eliminates the 90-day renewal cycle entirely for proxied domains. TLS 1.0/1.1 must be dropped — both are deprecated with known downgrade attacks.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>New domain needing HTTPS on any nginx virtual host</item>
        <item>Migrating from Let's Encrypt to a Cloudflare origin cert (eliminating renewal ops)</item>
        <item>Auditing TLS configuration for SSL Labs A+ score</item>
        <item>Adding HSTS or OCSP stapling to an existing nginx site</item>
        <item>Configuring SSL for a domain behind Cloudflare proxy</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Cloudflare Flexible mode — causes redirect loops when nginx redirects HTTP to HTTPS</item>
        <item>OCSP stapling with Cloudflare origin certs — they have no OCSP responder; only enable with Let's Encrypt or commercial certs</item>
        <item>Self-signed certs for production — use origin certs instead (trusted by Cloudflare edge)</item>
        <item>Adding preload to HSTS before confirming all subdomains support HTTPS — removal takes months</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="certificate-types">
      <p>Choose based on whether the domain uses Cloudflare proxy (orange cloud) or DNS-only (gray cloud).</p>
      <list>
        <item>Let's Encrypt — free, 90-day, auto-renewed by certbot systemd timer. Works with or without Cloudflare. Supports OCSP stapling.</item>
        <item>Cloudflare origin cert — free, 15 years, no renewal needed. Only trusted by Cloudflare edge (not by browsers directly). OCSP stapling not available.</item>
        <item>Self-signed — never use in production. Cloudflare reports 526 Invalid SSL Certificate.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="cloudflare-ssl-modes">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always use Full(Strict) when behind Cloudflare. Never use Flexible.</statement>
        <rationale>Flexible mode sends traffic from Cloudflare to your origin over plain HTTP. If nginx also enforces HTTPS redirects (as it should), this creates an infinite redirect loop (ERR_TOO_MANY_REDIRECTS).</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Off — HTTP everywhere, no encryption. Never use.</item>
        <item>Flexible — HTTPS browser→CF, HTTP CF→origin. Creates redirect loops + false security sense. Never use.</item>
        <item>Full — HTTPS CF→origin but accepts any certificate (self-signed OK). Better than Flexible but not recommended.</item>
        <item>Full(Strict) — HTTPS CF→origin, validates certificate. Use this. Requires a valid cert (origin cert or Let's Encrypt).</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="tls-versions">
      <p>Drop TLS 1.0 and 1.1 entirely. Minimum is TLS 1.2. TLS 1.3 is preferred — faster handshake, no cipher selection by server.</p>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
ssl_protocols TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="ocsp-stapling">
      <rule>
        <statement>Only enable OCSP stapling with Let's Encrypt or commercial certificates. Disable for Cloudflare origin certs.</statement>
        <rationale>Cloudflare origin certs are not issued by a public CA and have no OCSP responder. Enabling ssl_stapling with them causes nginx to log errors and potentially degrade TLS performance.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="ssl-params-snippet">
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
# /etc/nginx/snippets/ssl-params.conf
ssl_protocols             TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;
ssl_ciphers               ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384;
ssl_prefer_server_ciphers off;   # Let client choose for TLS 1.3

ssl_session_timeout 1d;
ssl_session_cache   shared:SSL:10m;   # ~40,000 sessions
ssl_session_tickets off;              # Disable for forward secrecy

# DH params for TLS 1.2 DHE ciphers (generate once)
# ssl_dhparam /etc/nginx/dhparam.pem;

# OCSP — only with Let's Encrypt or commercial certs; NOT Cloudflare origin certs
# ssl_stapling        on;
# ssl_stapling_verify on;
# resolver 1.1.1.1 8.8.8.8 valid=300s;
# resolver_timeout 5s;
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="http-to-https-redirect">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always add .well-known/acme-challenge exception to the HTTP→HTTPS redirect when using certbot.</statement>
        <rationale>certbot's HTTP-01 challenge verifies domain ownership by placing a file at /.well-known/acme-challenge/. If nginx redirects all HTTP to HTTPS, certbot cannot complete the challenge and certificate renewal fails.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
server {
    listen 80;
    server_name example.com;

    # Allow certbot HTTP challenge
    location /.well-known/acme-challenge/ {
        root /var/www/html;
    }

    location / {
        return 301 https://$host$request_uri;
    }
}
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="hsts">
      <p>Set HSTS with 2-year max-age. Add preload only after confirming all subdomains support HTTPS permanently.</p>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=63072000; includeSubDomains" always;
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="cloudflare-origin-cert-setup">
      <p>All NERO platform domains use Cloudflare Full(Strict) with a 15-year origin cert. Zero renewal ops.</p>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# 1. Generate in Cloudflare Dashboard: SSL/TLS → Origin Server → Create Certificate
# Hostnames: example.com, *.example.com | Validity: 15 years

# 2. Save to server
sudo mkdir -p /etc/nginx/ssl
sudo tee /etc/nginx/ssl/cloudflare-origin.pem      # paste certificate
sudo tee /etc/nginx/ssl/cloudflare-origin-key.pem  # paste private key
sudo chmod 600 /etc/nginx/ssl/cloudflare-origin-key.pem

# 3. nginx site config
server {
    listen 80;
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name example.com;

    ssl_certificate     /etc/nginx/ssl/cloudflare-origin.pem;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/nginx/ssl/cloudflare-origin-key.pem;
    include snippets/ssl-params.conf;

    include snippets/security-headers.conf;
    ...
}

# 4. Cloudflare Dashboard: SSL/TLS mode → Full (Strict)
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="letsencrypt-direct-domain">
      <p>For a domain not behind Cloudflare (gray cloud / DNS-only).</p>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
sudo apt install -y certbot python3-certbot-nginx

# Issue certificate (nginx plugin auto-configures nginx)
sudo certbot --nginx -d example.com -d www.example.com

# Test renewal
sudo certbot renew --dry-run

# Post-renewal hook to reload nginx
sudo mkdir -p /etc/letsencrypt/renewal-hooks/post
sudo tee /etc/letsencrypt/renewal-hooks/post/reload-nginx.sh << 'HOOK'
#!/bin/bash
systemctl reload nginx
HOOK
sudo chmod +x /etc/letsencrypt/renewal-hooks/post/reload-nginx.sh
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="troubleshooting-flexible-mode-redirect-loop">
      <example type="bad">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
# Symptom: ERR_TOO_MANY_REDIRECTS
# Cloudflare SSL mode: Flexible
# nginx forces HTTPS: return 301 https://...
#
# Cloudflare → origin HTTP → nginx redirects to HTTPS → Cloudflare sends HTTP → loop
        ]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
# Fix: Change Cloudflare SSL mode to Full (Strict)
# Cloudflare Dashboard → SSL/TLS → Full (Strict)
# Then place a valid origin cert on the server.
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="ssl-labs-score-verification">
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# CLI certificate check
echo | openssl s_client -connect example.com:443 2>/dev/null | openssl x509 -noout -dates -subject

# Test TLS version support
openssl s_client -connect example.com:443 -tls1_3  # should succeed
openssl s_client -connect example.com:443 -tls1    # should fail

# Check security headers
curl -sI https://example.com | grep -iE "strict-transport|x-content-type|x-frame"
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/ssl-params.conf" purpose="Reusable nginx snippet: TLS versions, ciphers, session settings, OCSP stapling toggle"/>
      <template path="templates/site-cloudflare.conf" purpose="nginx site template using Cloudflare origin cert"/>
      <template path="templates/site-letsencrypt.conf" purpose="nginx site template using Let's Encrypt cert with OCSP stapling"/>
      <template path="templates/setup-cloudflare-origin-cert.sh" purpose="Place origin cert + key in /etc/nginx/ssl/, set permissions"/>
    </templates>

    <scripts>
      <script path="scripts/check-cert-expiry.sh" purpose="Report cert expiry for all configured domains, warn at 30 days"/>
      <script path="scripts/test-tls-config.sh" purpose="Verify TLS versions, cipher score, HSTS header, OCSP response"/>
    </scripts>

    <see-also>
      <ref slug="nginx-reverse-proxy"/>
      <ref slug="server-init-bootstrap"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
